    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> Work through examples using the two-step approach. Encourage learners to write the base area calculation and volume calculation as separate steps.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Monitoring:</alert> Circulate during practice. Watch for learners who:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>Forget to multiply by <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> (using the cylinder formula instead).</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Confuse the height of the cone with the slant height.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Use the diameter instead of the radius in the formula.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Forget to square the radius (writing <m>\pi r h</m> instead of <m>\pi r^2 h</m>).</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

        <example xml:id="auto_bsjt0be2">
            <statement>
               <sidebyside>
                 <p xml:id="auto_2bafcvfj">
                    Find the volume of the following cone (correct to 1 decimal place):
                </p>
                <image width="30%">
               <latex-image label="cone-volume">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                     % Draw the entire cone with one uniform color
                    \fill[blue!40] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7) -- (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7) -- cycle;
                    \fill[blue!40] (-2,0) -- (0,4) -- (2,0) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw the base ellipse
                    \draw[thick] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7);
                    \draw[dashed] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7);
                    
                    % Draw the cone's sides
                    \draw[thick] (-2,0) -- (0,4);
                    \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (0,4);
                    
                    % Draw the height
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,4);
                    \node[left] at (0.4,2) {28cm};
                    
                    % Draw the radius
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                    \node[below] at (1,0) {14 cm};
                \end{tikzpicture}
               </latex-image>
               </image>
               </sidebyside> 
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_bix4o1qn">
                   Step 1: Find the area of the base .
                   <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Area of a Circle} = \amp \pi r^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{22}{7} \times 14\, \text{cm} \times 14 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 616{cm}^2 </mrow>
                   </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_nu6bi9x4">
                    Step 2: Calculate the volume
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{V} =\amp \frac{1}{3} \times \pi r^2\times H </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 616\, \text{cm}^2 \times 28\,  \text{cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow>  = 17, 248\, \text{cm}^3 \amp </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example> 

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The slant height of a cone is <m>13</m> cm and the radius of its base is <m>5</m> cm.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Find:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The vertical height of the cone.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The volume of the cone (Give your answer in terms of <m>\pi</m> and then correct to two decimal places).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                In a cone, the radius, height and slant height form a right-angled triangle.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>l^2 = r^2 + h^2</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Substitute <m>l = 13</m> and <m>r = 5</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                               <m>13^2 = 5^2 + h^2</m> 
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>169 = 25 + h^2</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m> h^2 = 144</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>h = 12 \;\text{ cm}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Use the volume formula
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> V =\amp \frac{1}{3}\pi r^2 h</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{3}\pi (5)^2 (12)</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{3}\pi (25)(12)</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{3}\pi (300)</mrow>
                                    <mrow> V = \amp 100\pi</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Therefore, <m>V = 100\pi \;\text{ cm}^3</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Using <m>\pi \approx 3.142</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>V \approx 314.16 \;\text{ cm}^3</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment – Exit Ticket</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 5 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            Learners complete individually to demonstrate understanding.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Question 1:</alert> An ice cream cone has a radius of <m>3</m> cm and a height of <m>8</m> cm. Estimate how much ice cream it can hold.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Question 2:</alert> Two cones have the same height of <m>84</m> cm but different radii. The first cone has a radius of <m>14</m> cm, and the second cone has a radius of <m>42</m> cm. Calculate and compare the volumes of the two cones. Which one has a larger volume?
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Answer Key:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Q1:</alert> <m>V = \frac{1}{3} \times \pi \times 3^2 \times 8 = \frac{1}{3} \times 3.14 \times 9 \times 8 \approx 75.36 \; \text{cm}^3</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Q2:</alert> First cone: <m>V = \frac{1}{3} \times \pi \times 14^2 \times 84 \approx 17\,248 \; \text{cm}^3</m>. Second cone: <m>V = \frac{1}{3} \times \pi \times 42^2 \times 84 \approx 155\,232 \; \text{cm}^3</m>. The second cone has a larger volume.
        </p>
    </axiom>

