    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>Provide pre-made cone models with labelled dimensions.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Use cones with simple whole-number dimensions for initial practice.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Pair struggling learners with confident problem solvers.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Break down the formula into steps: (1) Find base area <m>\pi r^2</m>, (2) Multiply by height, (3) Divide by 3.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Provide a step-by-step calculation template.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>On-Level Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>Verify the formula with the water pouring activity.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Explain the relationship between cones and cylinders to a peer.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Provide mixed practice with different dimensions, including problems where diameter is given instead of radius.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>Derive the formula using the relationship with cylinders.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Explore real-world applications: ice cream cones, funnels, traffic cones, conical tents.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Apply the concept to hollow cones (outer radius minus inner radius).</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Solve optimisation problems: Given a fixed volume, what dimensions minimise the surface area?</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Extension Activity — Cone-Shaped Funnel Investigation:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Work in groups.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol markers="1.">
                <li>
                    <p>Choose a real-world purpose for a cone-shaped funnel (e.g., pouring water, transferring grain, filtering liquids).</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Decide on the dimensions: radius and height.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Calculate the volume of your funnel using the cone formula.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>If the funnel needs to hold <m>500 \; \text{cm}^3</m> of liquid, what dimensions would work?</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Compare different funnel designs: tall and narrow vs. short and wide.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Present your findings with diagrams, measurements, and calculations.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx"/>

</section>